279
00:14:51,160 --> 00:14:54,910
a fantastic introduction to one
of the most amazing and central

280
00:14:54,910 --> 00:14:58,540
things that plants do for
the entire biosphere, which

281
00:14:58,540 --> 00:15:03,310
is to take solar energy that's
abundant but transient source

282
00:15:03,310 --> 00:15:06,820
of energy, and to capture that
energy through the process

283
00:15:06,820 --> 00:15:10,460
of photosynthesis,
interacting with CO2,

284
00:15:10,460 --> 00:15:13,810
with water to make sugars.

285
00:15:13,810 --> 00:15:18,380
And as probably even most
elementary school students know,

286
00:15:18,380 --> 00:15:20,380
the other thing, of course,
that comes from this

287
00:15:20,380 --> 00:15:22,420
is also very important
for the biosphere, which

288
00:15:22,420 --> 00:15:25,420
is oxygen, biomedical
oxygen, which we can breathe

289
00:15:25,420 --> 00:15:27,220
and which allows
respiration to be

290
00:15:27,220 --> 00:15:32,050
such an efficient process for
harvesting and using energy.

291
00:15:32,050 --> 00:15:34,870
So what I like to teach
my introductory students

292
00:15:34,870 --> 00:15:38,770
in biology, that we're taking
this transient source of energy

293
00:15:38,770 --> 00:15:43,340
and we're trapping that as the
bonds in the sugar molecules,

294
00:15:43,340 --> 00:15:43,840
right?

295
00:15:43,840 --> 00:15:47,480
So now we have this physical
thing that a plant or an animal

296
00:15:47,480 --> 00:15:50,092
can use to transport,
to move around,

297
00:15:50,092 --> 00:15:51,800
to use as energy when
they would like to.

298
00:15:51,800 --> 00:15:54,370
Not necessarily when
the sun is shining.

299
00:15:54,370 --> 00:15:58,210
But as you probably know, sugars
play a second equally important

300
00:15:58,210 --> 00:16:00,730
role, which is those
initially fixed

301
00:16:00,730 --> 00:16:03,820
carbon molecules form the
backbone of everything else.

302
00:16:03,820 --> 00:16:05,770
And I literally mean
everything else.

303
00:16:05,770 --> 00:16:08,080
Everything that the
plant makes, everything

304
00:16:08,080 --> 00:16:10,840
that an animal might eat
from that plant, everything

305
00:16:10,840 --> 00:16:13,870
that a fungus might use as
it decomposes that plant, all

306
00:16:13,870 --> 00:16:18,110
of those organic biomolecules
begin as carbon photosynthate.

307
00:16:18,110 --> 00:16:20,920
But there's also very
important other molecules

308
00:16:20,920 --> 00:16:23,870
that are part of that
fixation process.

309
00:16:23,870 --> 00:16:26,290
So you know we need
to eat protein,

310
00:16:26,290 --> 00:16:30,850
because protein contains
things like nitrogen and iron.

311
00:16:30,850 --> 00:16:33,560
Our lipids, of course,
are often very complex,

312
00:16:33,560 --> 00:16:35,240
large macromolecules.

313
00:16:35,240 --> 00:16:37,990
And not only the composition
of those molecules

314
00:16:37,990 --> 00:16:42,850
depends upon other nutrients,
but also the processes

315
00:16:42,850 --> 00:16:44,270
to generate those molecules.

316
00:16:44,270 --> 00:16:46,030
The very action of
doing photosynthesis

317
00:16:46,030 --> 00:16:48,730
requires all sorts of
interesting elements

318
00:16:48,730 --> 00:16:51,340
that are largely
gained from the soil.

319
00:16:51,340 --> 00:16:55,820
So what is the ultimate source
of those important components?

320
00:16:55,820 --> 00:16:59,580
Well, there's many, many
elements that organisms need.

321
00:16:59,580 --> 00:17:01,260
Plants and us.

322
00:17:01,260 --> 00:17:03,150
Nitrogen is often
was thought about,

323
00:17:03,150 --> 00:17:06,480
but there's also countless
mineral molecules.

324
00:17:06,480 --> 00:17:07,970
Where do those come from?

325
00:17:07,970 --> 00:17:10,790
Well, ultimately, those
are weathered off of rocks.

326
00:17:10,790 --> 00:17:12,829
There are abundant
sources of many

327
00:17:12,829 --> 00:17:14,690
of these minerals
in the lithosphere

328
00:17:14,690 --> 00:17:17,130
and as rocks weather,
those enter the soils,

329
00:17:17,130 --> 00:17:19,290
those can be captured by
the biosphere, by capture,

330
00:17:19,290 --> 00:17:23,030
by plants and microbes
to build their biomass.

331
00:17:23,030 --> 00:17:25,790
Nitrogen is also
incredibly abundant

332
00:17:25,790 --> 00:17:27,800
but is abundant
in our atmosphere

333
00:17:27,800 --> 00:17:30,440
as nitrogen gas, N2 gas.

334
00:17:30,440 --> 00:17:33,267
And you may know that nitrogen
gas is incredibly hard

335
00:17:33,267 --> 00:17:35,100
to break apart those
two nitrogen molecules.

336
00:17:35,100 --> 00:17:37,058
But breaking apart those
two nitrogen molecules

337
00:17:37,058 --> 00:17:39,710
is critical to
turn that nitrogen

338
00:17:39,710 --> 00:17:44,060
into usable forms of nutrients
like ammonia nitrate, which

339
00:17:44,060 --> 00:17:46,320
plants can uptake,
turn into proteins,

340
00:17:46,320 --> 00:17:48,690
thus providing us
with a food source.

341
00:17:48,690 --> 00:17:51,180
Now in natural
communities, which

342
00:17:51,180 --> 00:17:53,580
I have grown up studying as
an evolutionary biologist

343
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:56,820
and ecologist, in
natural communities where

344
00:17:56,820 --> 00:18:00,390
plants and animals and microbes
are found and where they thrive

345
00:18:00,390 --> 00:18:03,660
is really a function of
what's in those environments.

346
00:18:03,660 --> 00:18:05,978
If there's rocks nearby
that can weather out

347
00:18:05,978 --> 00:18:08,520
these important minerals, well,
then the kinds of plants that

348
00:18:08,520 --> 00:18:11,700
can make use of those minerals
or that do well when they're

349
00:18:11,700 --> 00:18:14,590
in excess or in deficit, and
similarly, for nitrogen, where

350
00:18:14,590 --> 00:18:16,090
there's enough
nitrogen in the soil,

351
00:18:16,090 --> 00:18:18,090
there's plants that will
thrive in those places.

352
00:18:18,090 --> 00:18:19,798
And if they don't
thrive in those places,

353
00:18:19,798 --> 00:18:21,330
in those natural
communities, well,

354
00:18:21,330 --> 00:18:24,150
then they can move someplace
else, or they might go extinct.

355
00:18:24,150 --> 00:18:26,370
So natural communities
have evolved

356
00:18:26,370 --> 00:18:29,070
over hundreds of thousands
and millions of years

357
00:18:29,070 --> 00:18:31,710
to have compositions
of plants and animals

358
00:18:31,710 --> 00:18:34,410
and fungi that
form the biosphere.

359
00:18:34,410 --> 00:18:36,443
Some plants die, they rot.

360
00:18:36,443 --> 00:18:37,860
They create nutrients
for microbes

361
00:18:37,860 --> 00:18:41,670
which produce and sort of
continue the cycle of life.

362
00:18:41,670 --> 00:18:44,160
But in agricultural
systems, we don't

363
00:18:44,160 --> 00:18:47,590
have that same nice
balance, unfortunately.

364
00:18:47,590 --> 00:18:50,200
It's not simply a matter of
having the plants grow someplace

365
00:18:50,200 --> 00:18:52,158
else, because we want to
have those plants grow

366
00:18:52,158 --> 00:18:53,950
at very high yield,
in the places where

367
00:18:53,950 --> 00:18:55,360
we need them to be growing.

368
00:18:55,360 --> 00:18:58,420
And so that creates a real
problem when any of these things

369
00:18:58,420 --> 00:19:00,520
become out of balance.

370
00:19:00,520 --> 00:19:03,190
And this has led to what
has been called the nitrogen

371
00:19:03,190 --> 00:19:04,030
problem.

372
00:19:04,030 --> 00:19:07,000
So we know that nitrogen is a
key limiting nutrient for most

373
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:09,370
of our agricultural production.

374
00:19:09,370 --> 00:19:10,990
Most of our calories
in the world

375
00:19:10,990 --> 00:19:15,050
come from cereals, either that
we eat directly, corn and wheat,

376
00:19:15,050 --> 00:19:19,153
or that we feed to our animals,
which we then eat the animals.

377
00:19:19,153 --> 00:19:21,320
And to maintain these very
high yields from cereals,

378
00:19:21,320 --> 00:19:23,300
we need to have a lot
of nitrogen fertilizer.

379
00:19:23,300 --> 00:19:25,340
As I told you, those
things can become limiting.

380
00:19:25,340 --> 00:19:27,380
If you imagine a common
agricultural year,

381
00:19:27,380 --> 00:19:29,800
you're pulling up all that
biomass, you're shipping it off

382
00:19:29,800 --> 00:19:31,400
and the nitrogen
is going with it.

383
00:19:31,400 --> 00:19:33,910
So we're constantly adding more
and more nitrogen fertilizer

384
00:19:33,910 --> 00:19:35,200
back to the soil.

385
00:19:35,200 --> 00:19:38,770
The predominant source of the
nitrogen in the developed world

386
00:19:38,770 --> 00:19:41,980
is through industrial
fixation of nitrogen

387
00:19:41,980 --> 00:19:43,670
through the Haber-Bosch process.

388
00:19:43,670 --> 00:19:45,790
Here's a few figures to
make the point to you

389
00:19:45,790 --> 00:19:48,250
that this is an incredibly
resource intensive process

390
00:19:48,250 --> 00:19:50,020
to capture that
atmospheric nitrogen

391
00:19:50,020 --> 00:19:52,920
and turn it into ammonia that
we can feed to our plants.

392
00:19:52,920 --> 00:19:56,440
So just huge proportions of
the total global carbon budget

393
00:19:56,440 --> 00:19:59,470
come from the process of
making industrial nitrogen.

394
00:19:59,470 --> 00:20:01,870
But even more
depressing is that most

395
00:20:01,870 --> 00:20:03,370
of the nitrogen we
put onto our soil

396
00:20:03,370 --> 00:20:06,380
doesn't end up in our plants and
doesn't end up in us as food.

397
00:20:06,380 --> 00:20:08,140
It's running off, or
it's being lost back

398
00:20:08,140 --> 00:20:10,940
to the atmosphere as
climate changing gases.

399
00:20:10,940 --> 00:20:12,668
So this is the nitrogen problem.

400
00:20:12,668 --> 00:20:14,210
Now, you're probably
aware that there

401
00:20:14,210 --> 00:20:18,530
are plants out there that have,
in a sense, figured this out.

402
00:20:18,530 --> 00:20:22,140
So in places where nitrogen
in the soil is very limiting,

403
00:20:22,140 --> 00:20:26,630
microbes can fix that
nitrogen. Atmospheric nitrogen.

404
00:20:26,630 --> 00:20:28,160
And many plants
have figured out how

405
00:20:28,160 --> 00:20:32,180
to coexist with those microbes
and make use of that nitrogen.

406
00:20:32,180 --> 00:20:33,680
So there's this
really nice exchange

407
00:20:33,680 --> 00:20:36,300
of carbon from the plant and
nitrogen from the microbes.

408
00:20:36,300 --> 00:20:39,350
And of course, legumes like
soybeans and many other beans

409
00:20:39,350 --> 00:20:41,150
are the most famous
and widespread example

410
00:20:41,150 --> 00:20:43,910
of this in our food system.

411
00:20:43,910 --> 00:20:45,327
But cereals don't
have this trick.

412
00:20:45,327 --> 00:20:47,743
They don't have-- and they
haven't figured out how to have

413
00:20:47,743 --> 00:20:50,660
that symbiosis, how to get these
relationships with microbes

414
00:20:50,660 --> 00:20:53,750
to provide nitrogen. So this has
really been sort of a moonshot

415
00:20:53,750 --> 00:20:56,508
genetic engineering project
since at least the 1970s.

416
00:20:56,508 --> 00:20:58,550
And a number of proposals
have been brought forth

417
00:20:58,550 --> 00:21:01,430
about how we might try to
introduce this nitrogen capture

418
00:21:01,430 --> 00:21:05,510
process into our cereal crops.

419
00:21:05,510 --> 00:21:08,238
So at base, what
this issue is, is

420
00:21:08,238 --> 00:21:10,280
how do we get the nitrogen
out of the atmosphere,

421
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:14,120
into a microbe, and into the
plants we want those microbes

422
00:21:14,120 --> 00:21:15,500
to be associated with?

423
00:21:15,500 --> 00:21:17,210
And in turn, what
is the plant then

424
00:21:17,210 --> 00:21:19,370
giving back to those
microbes in exchange

425
00:21:19,370 --> 00:21:21,650
for this resource, this
valuable, energetically

426
00:21:21,650 --> 00:21:25,030
intensive resource capture?

427
00:21:25,030 --> 00:21:26,860
So this is the central question.

428
00:21:26,860 --> 00:21:29,800
And this is a
question, a challenge

429
00:21:29,800 --> 00:21:32,590
that we've been tackling as
part of the MIT Climate Grand

430
00:21:32,590 --> 00:21:35,320
Challenge Program, led by Chris
Voigt, a number of faculty

431
00:21:35,320 --> 00:21:37,960
from across the Institute
where we're trying to address

432
00:21:37,960 --> 00:21:41,975
this nutrient use in agriculture
problem in a very holistic way.

433
00:21:41,975 --> 00:21:43,600
And what I want to
share with you today

434
00:21:43,600 --> 00:21:45,800
is a small piece
of that project,

435
00:21:45,800 --> 00:21:49,180
which is trying to optimize this
particular little interaction.

436
00:21:49,180 --> 00:21:51,890
How do we get those microbes
to capture the nitrogen,

437
00:21:51,890 --> 00:21:54,610
give it to the plants that
we want them to give it to,

438
00:21:54,610 --> 00:21:57,550
under the conditions that we
need them to do so, and then

439
00:21:57,550 --> 00:22:01,800
have the microbes in a sense
cultivated by the plants.

440
00:22:01,800 --> 00:22:04,830
So Professor Chris Voight
here in MIT's bioengineering

441
00:22:04,830 --> 00:22:07,320
department, is really focusing
on this first question.

442
00:22:07,320 --> 00:22:09,720
How do we genetically
engineer bacteria

443
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:14,200
to fix the nitrogen when and
where we need them to do it?

444
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:17,330
My group is really interested
in the plant side of this.

445
00:22:17,330 --> 00:22:19,720
My group is comprised of
plant physiologists, plant

446
00:22:19,720 --> 00:22:21,820
geneticists, and we
think very deeply

447
00:22:21,820 --> 00:22:25,000
about how plant performance
is driven and affected

448
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,740
by environmental conditions
and environmental change.

449
00:22:27,740 --> 00:22:29,240
And one thing we've
been focusing on

450
00:22:29,240 --> 00:22:31,115
in the last few years
is trying to understand

451
00:22:31,115 --> 00:22:34,060
under what conditions
do plants provide

452
00:22:34,060 --> 00:22:37,210
these cheap carbohydrates,
organic acids and sugars

453
00:22:37,210 --> 00:22:39,160
to the microbes in the soil.

454
00:22:39,160 --> 00:22:41,450
Is there genetic
variation in this process?

455
00:22:41,450 --> 00:22:43,070
How does the
environment drive this?

456
00:22:43,070 --> 00:22:45,310
And critically,
could we understand

457
00:22:45,310 --> 00:22:50,280
at a mechanistic level how
to manipulate that process?

458
00:22:50,280 --> 00:22:52,660
These are some really key
questions we're interested in.

459
00:22:52,660 --> 00:22:55,060
What molecules are
there being produced?

460
00:22:55,060 --> 00:22:57,100
Does the environment
drive this process?

461
00:22:57,100 --> 00:22:58,560
And critically,
can we manipulate

462
00:22:58,560 --> 00:23:01,460
the production of what
we call these accidents?

463
00:23:01,460 --> 00:23:04,310
Now to do this requires
a tremendous amount

464
00:23:04,310 --> 00:23:06,170
of technological know how.

465
00:23:06,170 --> 00:23:08,893
So we're looking at roots,
so they're below ground.

466
00:23:08,893 --> 00:23:10,310
We can't just walk
up to the plant

467
00:23:10,310 --> 00:23:12,650
and measure them without
disrupting itself.

468
00:23:12,650 --> 00:23:15,590
So we're collaborating
with a Professor Sixian You

469
00:23:15,590 --> 00:23:19,200
here in MIT's research lab
