470
00:23:19,200 --> 00:23:23,330
who's developed non-label,
non-invasive imaging

471
00:23:23,330 --> 00:23:27,200
technologies for living tissue,
where we can look at the roots

472
00:23:27,200 --> 00:23:30,240
in situ, as they're growing,
and look at their metabolism,

473
00:23:30,240 --> 00:23:32,157
look at their chemistry,
look, see how they're

474
00:23:32,157 --> 00:23:33,590
growing at the cellular level.

475
00:23:33,590 --> 00:23:36,650
And my PhD student,
Chloe Heitmeyer,

476
00:23:36,650 --> 00:23:38,790
has developed a
very simple system

477
00:23:38,790 --> 00:23:40,790
to grow these plants under
controlled conditions

478
00:23:40,790 --> 00:23:42,560
where we can actually
then image them

479
00:23:42,560 --> 00:23:45,350
in situ, and critically
sample those exudates

480
00:23:45,350 --> 00:23:46,830
from living plants.

481
00:23:46,830 --> 00:23:49,050
So as I introduced
the beginning,

482
00:23:49,050 --> 00:23:50,310
I'm a plant biologist, right?

483
00:23:50,310 --> 00:23:52,650
And when I talk to my
colleagues at the universities,

484
00:23:52,650 --> 00:23:54,025
they say, well,
what on Earth are

485
00:23:54,025 --> 00:23:56,630
you doing in this environmental
engineering department at MIT?

486
00:23:56,630 --> 00:23:58,280
And this is what I'm doing here.

487
00:23:58,280 --> 00:24:01,228
The opportunity to collaborate
with electrical engineers

488
00:24:01,228 --> 00:24:03,270
and to recruit the best
PhD students in the world

489
00:24:03,270 --> 00:24:05,410
to come and work in the
